{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":4364,"record_hash":"sha256:9ec0f4f8a49142ac47bb5e0e1614c8dddb28708094a6283ad212ecfa9d3ba0fe","timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:41:42.315Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"::code-comment{title=\"[P1] Path whitelist lets base64 secrets through\" body=\"`/` is part of the candidate alphabet, but `is_pathish()` treats any candidate starting with `/` or containing at least two slashes as safe. That means normal base64-looking credentials with slashes can exceed the entropy threshold and still remain unredacted. I would remove or heavily tighten this whitelist; over-redacting a path in `source_record` is less risky than missing opaque secrets.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=145 end=146 priority=1 confidence=0.92}\n\n::code-comment{title=\"[P2] Hex secrets are effectively exempt\" body=\"Pure hex strings cannot exceed 4 bits of entropy per character, so the `> 4.0` threshold will not catch them; then 40- and 64-character hex strings are explicitly treated as common hashes. That preserves commit/SHA-looking values, but it also lets common hex-encoded credentials or HMAC keys pass unchanged.\" file=\"/Users/kiril/src/gitbutler/crates/but-agentlog/src/redaction.rs\" start=116 end=118 priority=2 confidence=0.86}\n\nThe cleanup-only agent found two tiny P3 style nits: `RedactedValue` is a one-use wrapper, and `should_redact()` is a one-line helper. I would not prioritize those until after the two redaction behavior issues above. The P1 is the one I’d fix first.","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-07T15:41:42.315Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"assistant","phase":"final_answer"}}}